This bow is rumoured to have once belonged to a great captain of Doriath, before Beleriand fell into the Sea, borne by the long tides to the shores of Middle-earth.
This is one of three bows named after the Winds from which Men oft seek tidings of the world. The West Wind is the wandering Wind.
This bow was once borne by one of the greatest hunters in the Shire. He oft brought down his quarry with a single, well-placed arrow.
This is one of three bows named after the Winds from which Men oft seek tidings of the world. The North Wind blows from the Gate of Kings.
This crossbow was crafted by a great dwarf-smith of the Grey Mountains when the dragons first came out of the North. Unfortunately, a single crossbow could not stop a horde.
This mechanical bow was crafted by the Men of Angmar for use in the wars against the North Kingdom long ago. Perhaps it may be put to the cause of good.
This mechanical bow, crafted in the forges of Carn Dûm, slew many Men of Arnor before it was lost. Now it may be used to avenge the memory of those it slew.
This axe came from the armouries of Khazad-dûm long before it was known as Moria, long before the darkness came.
This axe was used by a brave Bree-man to try and lay to rest the first barrow-wights as they appeared in the old Downs. Unfortunately one brave man was not enough.
This axe was wielded by a guardsman who watched the gates of one of the ancient dwarf-kingdoms which fell to ruin within the Blue Mountains.
It is believed that it was with this axe that Fram slew the mighty dragon Scatha long ago.
This axe, etched with the image of a ship upon the Sea, was forged in memory of Númenor that was.
This axe was borne by a guardsman of Khazad-dûm in the early ages of the world. To what end the guard came is unknown, though some say he awoke Durin's Bane.
This axe was forged by one of the greatest dwarf-smiths of the now-ruined kingdoms which once lay within the heart of the Blue Mountains.
The bit of this dwarf-forged axe has been honed to the finest edge for the greatest effectiveness in battle.
This club was crafted by the Woodmen from wood felled by Orcs. It is believed to grant it's bearer the endurance of the forest.
This club was borne across the Misty Mountains by the fathers of the Stoors. It proved that Stone-trolls are not completely impervious to wood.
This club has weathered many battles over the centuries and still has many more to go.
This club was borne by a hobbit-captain in the last battle of Fornost. Legend has it that it was used to slay a great captain of Angmar.
This club was used to protect the leaf-fields of Longbottom against the ruffians stirring trouble in the Southfarthing.
This club is so big that Shire-folk say only a descendant of the Bullroarer Took would be able to wield it.
This club was crafted by a Staddle-hobbit in hopes of becoming a legend in the Midgewater Marshes. He became a legend after he went missing.
This club was crafted by the Woses of the Drúadan Forest in Anórien. It is believed that the cunning of that folk remains in the weapon.
This knife has been carried for generations the dwarf-hunters of the Grey Mountains, but it was lost when the dragons came from the North and drove Durin's Folk away.
This dagger was forged in the kingdom of Arnor to defend against the tyranny of Angmar.
Gilnaith is believed to have been worn at the belt of the last great Elf-king, Gil-galad, as he marched to Mordor with the last great Alliance of Elves and Men.
The blade of this dagger is crafted in such away as to catch and the edge of an opposing weapon, allowing Remmenolf's wielder to more easily parry attacks.
Resolve was crafted in Dale in the days of Girion. The virtue of this halberd is to renew the bearer's vigour, whilst sapping the strength of the enemy.
This halberd of the Galadhrim was forged to defend the borders of Lothlórien from the Orcs of Moria after the dwarves were driven hence.
This halberd was borne by a door-warden of Meduseld in Edoras long ago. What became of the warden is not written.
This spear was borne by one of the Horse-lords of the Riddermark in elder days for hunting the great boars of Rohan.
This spear was crafted by a hunter from Needlehole for the purpose of ridding Rushock Bog of the monstrous toads which dwell there. You have to be quick to skewer a toad.
This spear was crafted in the North Kingdom of Arnor, before it broke into the three Kingdoms of the North, Arthedain, Cardolan, and Rhudaur. It was lost in the wars with Angmar.
This staff was crafted in Lothlórien to defend against the power of Dul Guldur in the days of the Necromancer.
This staff, brought to Middle-earth from Númenor by a lore-master in service to Elendil, is believed to have the power to renew the strength of its bearer.
This staff was once borne by the Old Took in his 'respectable' days. It was stolen by a nephew who went adventuring.
This staff was borne by the Chief Gate-warden of the White Mountains. It was believed to have the power to drive away the spirits which haunt the White Mountains.
